=== TASK ===
# Manual Payment Collection (Stripe Connect - Payment Links)

## Overview
This feature enables concierge/admin staff to initiate manual payment collection for inquiries using Stripe Connect Payment Links or hosted Stripe Checkout sessions. Admins can create payment links tied to specific inquiries, guests complete payments via Stripe-hosted checkout/Payment Links, and Stripe webhooks automatically update the platform’s payment state. A manual reconciliation UI allows staff to mark payments received, attach notes, and reconcile offline if needed. All Stripe credentials are securely stored; connected accounts are supported when hosts require payouts.

## Components to Build
1) Stripe Connect Abstraction Layer
- Purpose: Encapsulate creation of Payment Links and Checkout Sessions for either platform-wide or connected accounts.
- Responsibilities:
  - Create Payment Link or Checkout Session with metadata linking to inquiryId, guestId, and host/account details.
  - Optional: specify deposit vs. full payment amount, currency, and expiration.
  - Support connected accounts (hosts) via Stripe Connect if required; fall back to platform account when necessary.
  - Retrieve and store Stripe object IDs (payment_link_id, checkout_session_id) and status in your database.
  - Handle idempotency to prevent duplicate links for the same inquiry.
- Data: Stripe account IDs, API keys/tokens, webhook signing secret.

2) Webhook Endpoint for Stripe Connect
- Purpose: Listen to Stripe events to update inquiry/payment state automatically.
- Events to handle: checkout.session.completed, payment_intent.succeeded, charge.succeeded (if used), payment_intent.payment_failed, payment_link.created/updated (optional for auditing).
- Security: Verify webhook signatures using Stripe's signing secret; robust replay protection; idempotent updates.
- Actions:
  - Map Stripe event data to internal inquiry status (e.g., Deposit Paid, Fully Paid, Payment Failed).
  - Store payment details (amount, currency, timestamp, payment method, stripe_account) in a payments table.
  - Trigger downstream workflows: send receipt, update inquiry status, notify concierge.

3) Admin/Concierge Payment Link Management
- Admin UI components to:
  - Create a new payment link or checkout session tied to an inquiry.
  - Choose payment amount (deposit/total), currency, and whether to use a hosted Checkout or Payment Link landing page.
  - Display generated Stripe link, expiration, and related metadata.
  - Override or mark as paid for reconciliation purposes, with optional notes.
- Data: inquiry reference, amount, metadata, stripe_link_id, stripe_session_id, status, createdAt, updatedAt.

4) Public Checkout Page (Payment Completion)
- Public-facing page that guests land on after clicking the Stripe payment link.
- Purpose: present a minimal branded Stripe-hosted payment experience (Checkout) and return user to platform with payment status.
- Behavior: After successful payment, Stripe redirects or sends webhook; platform should capture and reflect payment status in the guest’s inquiry.
- Optional: Custom host-facing landing page that embeds Stripe Payment Links (if hosting page is preferred); otherwise rely on Stripe-hosted checkout flow.

5) Reconciliation UI
- Backend UI for staff to:
  - See pending deposits, partial payments, and full payments.
  - Attach reconciliation notes, attach documents, and mark status transitions.
  - Export to CSV for accounting.
- Data: reconciliationNotes, reconciliationStatus, attachedFiles, reconciliationDate.

6) Security & Compliance Layer
- Secrets management for Stripe keys (platform and connected accounts).
- Least-privilege API keys and scoped access based on user role (Guest, Host, Concierge).
- Proper validation and sanitization of all inputs that interact with Stripe.
- PCI considerations: minimize PCI scope by using Stripe-hosted checkout; never collect raw card data via your servers.

